<!-- Reflection Section -->
<div class="reflection">
    <h3>Reflection:</h3>
    <p><strong>Importance of Understanding Chemical Composition:</strong>  
        Knowing the chemical composition of products gives us better control over what we consume. For example, understanding the presence of ''carbonated water (H₂O)'' in Coca-Cola, ''sucrose (C₁₂H₂₂O₁₁)'' in Milk Loaded, and ''sodium chloride (NaCl)'' in Safeguard helps us make informed decisions about our health. These insights can affect our choices regarding nutrition, environmental impact, and overall well-being. When we understand how these substances work in our body and environment, we become more mindful consumers. It’s empowering to know how everyday items are connected to science.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Why Manufacturers Don't Use Chemical Names:</strong>  
        Manufacturers opt for simpler, non-technical terms to make products more approachable. Chemical names can sound complex, so using names like ''Sodium Chloride'' instead of ''NaCl'' or ''Sucrose'' instead of its full formula makes it easier for the average consumer to understand. This strategy helps bridge the gap between scientific knowledge and the general public, ensuring that consumers feel more confident about the products they are using without being overwhelmed by scientific jargon.
    </p>
</div>

